<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09025c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09025c">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09025c"> 25(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ shoot formation ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>The Garden</b>. &hellip; The plant is kept pruned to a single main stem furnished from bottom to top with fruit spurs. The particular form is secured by systematically cutting back in the pruning season all lateral shoots to two or three buds. This has the effect of checking shoot formation and of encouraging the storage of reserve food in each of the shortened branches, followed by the development of &ldquo;fruit buds.&rdquo; <small> <a name="IS23feb24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#IS23feb24"><cite title="source">Irish Statesman</cite></a> (23 February 1924) 765/1-2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c03070i" href="c03all.htm#c03070i">VI.C.03:070(i)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
